When to use scanf():

You’re reading numbers (int, float, etc.)

You’re reading a single word (no spaces)

You want to parse input that follows a specific pattern (e.g., "%d,%f")


Limitations:

Stops reading at whitespace (space, tab, newline) — so it cannot read strings with spaces.

Leaves the newline (\n) in the input buffer, which can cause issues if you later use fgets().

Easy to misuse and cause buffer overflows if not careful with string sizes.

________________________________________

When to use fgets():

You want to read an entire line of text

You want to include spaces

You want safe input (it prevents buffer overflow)

You plan to process the input string manually later (e.g., using sscanf, atoi, etc.)






Feature				scanf()			fgets()
=====================================================================================
Reads numbers easily		✅			❌ (need atoi, sscanf, etc.)
Reads strings with spaces	❌			✅
Prevents buffer overflow	❌			✅
Reads until whitespace		✅			❌ (reads until newline or buffer full)
Good for mixed text/numbers     ⚠️ (tricky)		✅ (with parsing)
Leaves newline in buffer	✅			❌ (reads it in, can remove manually)


